{Migraine with Aura: Migraine headaches can cause neurological symptoms like parasthesia and photophobia. Weakness may be experienced during or after an attack.}, {Meningitis: Inflammation of the meninges (membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord) can cause all three symptoms, often with fever and a stiff neck.}, {Encephalitis: Brain inflammation can cause a range of neurological symptoms including parasthesia, photophobia, and weakness, often accompanied by fever and confusion.}, {Stroke: Weakness on one side of the body is a key symptom, and parasthesia can occur. Photophobia is less common but possible.}, {Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA): Similar to stroke but temporary, it can cause these symptoms, especially numbness or tingling (parasthesia).}, {Multiple Sclerosis: This autoimmune disease can cause a wide variety of neurological symptoms, including all those mentioned, as it disrupts nerve signals.}, {Vitamin B12 Deficiency: Severe deficiency can lead to nerve damage, causing parasthesia, weakness, and fatigue. Photophobia is less common but possible.}, {Lyme Disease: If the nervous system is affected (neuroborreliosis), it can cause these symptoms along with others like facial palsy.}, {Brain Tumor: Depending on location and size, a tumor can cause a variety of neurological symptoms, potentially including all three mentioned.}, {Guillain-Barré Syndrome: This autoimmune disorder affects the peripheral nerves and can cause weakness, often starting in the legs, along with parasthesia. Photophobia is less common.}
